## Global Warming Analysis (Summary)

### Summary

#### Code

The assignment provided helper code including the class `Climate` which processed a .csv file containing temperature
the temperature data used in the analysis. The code used regular expressions to construct a dictionary mapping cities
and dates to temperatures. With the exception of the `se_over_slope` function, all methods outside of the climate class
were implemented as part of the assignment. This included eight methods for plotting data, generating data statistics,
generating model statistics, and evaluating models on training and testing data. The methods were

- `generate_models`: generate model of specified degree
- `r_squared`: compute r^2 value
- `evaluate_models_on_training`: plot data, plot model fit, and report summary stats on training data
- `gen_cities_avg`: compute average temp across a group of cities
- `moving_average`: compute moving average over a specified time span
- `rsme`: compute root mean squared error
- `evaluate_models_on_testing`: plot data, plot model fit, and report summary stats on testing data
-`gen_std_devs`: compute a particular standard deviation of temps

The python library `pylab`-- now `numpy`-- was used for modeling and data analysis. The assignment is rather old hence
the use of `pylab`. However, all functions used in the assignment have the same functionality in `numpy`. The library
`re` was also used as part of the `Climate` class, but again this was provided in the helper code.

#### Average Temperature
In order to asses claims related to global warming temperature in major USA cities was analyzed over the course of
1960-2016. The period 1960-2009 (inclusive) formed the training data while the period (2010-2016) formed the test data.
The final date in the data set was 12/31/2015. Temperature was measured in degrees Celsius

Temperatures were analyzed at the daily level and annual level for New York City, and then for the average of major US
cities-- including yearly averages and 5 year moving averages.

The training data was used to fit degree 1, degree 2, degree 20 models. The code generates a number scatterplots
visualizing year vs temperature and evaluates models fit to training and/or test data.


#### Temperature Variation

Additionally, the standard deviation of 5 year moving average temperature was analyzed to explore claims of increased
variation in temperature. A degree 1 model was fit to the training data.

#### Conclusions

Analysis showed evidence of global warming in the training and test data. The linear model provided the best predictive
model out of sample with the higher degree models suffering from considerable overfitting. In particular the degree 20
model performed particularly poorly out of sample despite performing well in sample-- this behavior was expected.
Notably, both the degree 2 and degree 20 model performed worse than random on out of sample data (e.g. guessing the
average).

The limited analysis of temperature variation showed a decrease in average temperature volatility in the training set.
This result was surprising given anecdotal evidence of especially hot or cold seasons. However, the writeup discusses
the limitations of the current analysis. Specifically, analyzing the 5 year moving average does not examine the behavior
of extreme values in the data set (e.g. min and max temperatures) and may even supress the behavior of extreme
temperatures. As a result, the current analysis of temperature variation indicates very little and a more direct
examination of extreme temperatures (e.g. max or min temperatures) is suggested.